  "text": "Before matching, we perform simple a pre-processing step on the schemas by merging syntactically similar attributes (e.g., \"title of book\" is merged to \"title\"). In particular, we conduct a manual syntactic merging for the BAMM dataset and further fully automate this process for the TEL-8 databset by exploiting the syntactic similarity of both attribute names and instance values [CITATION_1] . This pre-processing action serves for two purposes: First, it shows that syntactic merging cannot discover all the matchings, especially the \"semantically difficult\" ones. For instance, in Movies domain, star and actor are synonyms, but they bear essentially no syntactic similarity in names. Also, both of them are only associated with input boxes and thus have no instance values. As our experiment shows, many popular matchings are indeed \"semantically difficult.\" Second, syntactic merging, by increasing the frequency of merged attributes, can enhance the accuracy of holistic matching approaches. The reason is that as statistical methods, these approaches rely on \"sufficient observations\" of attribute occurrences and thus they are likely to perform more favorably for frequent attributes.",
